atural philosophers the lexicon with which to explain language’s ability to move individuals without physical contact. These writers and thinkers came to see eloquence as an aesthetic force capable of binding, drawing, softening, and scattering audiences. Bringing together a range of examples from drama, poetry, and philosophy by Bacon, Lodge, Marlowe, Montaigne, Shakespeare, and more, Mann demonstrates that the fascination with Orpheus produced some of the most canonical literature of the age.Delving into the impact of ancient Greek thought and poetry in the early modern era, The Trials of Orpheus sheds light on how the powers of rhetoric became a focus of English thought and literature.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aEloquence in literature. 0aEnglish literaturexGreek influences. 0aEnglish literatureyEarly modern, 1500-1700xHistory and criticism. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Ancient & Classical.2bisacsh  aAbjection.  aAlchemy.  aAristaeus.  aAristotelianism.  aArthur Golding.  aAstrophel and Stella.  aAutoeroticism.  aBacchanalia.  aBacchides (play).  aCaelum.  aCato the Younger.  aClaudian.  aCreation myth.  aCritique.  aCupid.  aDe Inventione.  aDe rerum natura.  aDemocritus.  aDionysus.  aDoctor Faustus (play).  aDomitius Marsus.  aDrama.  aElocutio.  aEloquence.  aEpithet.  aEpyllion.  aEssay.  aEuripides.  aExcursus.  aExplanatory gap.  aFrancis Beaumont.  aGenealogia Deorum Gentilium.  aGeorge Gascoigne.  aGeorge Puttenham.  aGiambattista della Porta.  aGiovanni Boccaccio.  aGreco-Roman mysteries.  aGreek mythology.  aHermaphroditus.  aHermeticism.  aHeroides.  aHimeros (Parthian).  aHippolytus (play).  aInception.  aInventio.  aIphigenia in Aulis.  aJohn Ashbery.  aL'Orfeo.  aLingua (play).  aLucretia.  aL